0long%20legacy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3ECreating%20a%20'very%20fast%2C%20very%20high-flying'%20reconnaissance%20aircraft%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%225100%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20American%20spy%20plane%20Lockheed%20A-12%20Oxcart%20in%20flight.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659baf291c5c7b8c9a0eb120%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%224126%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20American%20spy%20plane%20Lockheed%20A-12%20Oxcart%20in%20flight.%3Cp%3ECollection%20Bernard%20Crochet%2FPhoto12%2FUniversal%20Images%20Group%20via%20Getty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20the%201950s%20and%2060s%2C%20the%20CIA%20developed%20the%20aircraft%20under%20the%20OXCART%20Project%20to%20succeed%20the%20famed%20U-2%20spy%20plane.%20Lockheed%20won%20the%20contract%20for%20the%20OXCART%20Project%2C%20and%20Clarence%20%26quot%3BKelly%26quot%3B%20Johnson%2C%20a%20legendary%20aerospace%20engineer%2C%20began%20developing%20the%20aircraft%20in%201959.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20A-12%20was%20the%2012th%20iteration%20under%20the%20code%20name%20Archangel%2C%20featuring%20%26quot%3Bcutting-edge%20innovations%20in%20titanium%20fabrication%2C%20lubricants%2C%20jet%20engines%2C%20fuel%2C%20navigation%2C%20flight%20control%2C%20electronic%20countermeasures%2C%20radar%20stealthiness%2C%20and%20pilot%20life-support%20systems%2C%26quot%3B%20according%20to%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cia.gov%2Flegacy%2Fmuseum%2Fexhibit%2Fa-12-oxcart%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ECIA%20website%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3ETesting%20in%20Area%2051%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221600%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22area%2051%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F54b541396da8115d69360981%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221067%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EEntrance%20to%20Area%2051%3Cp%3ETIFO%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EIts%20development%20was%20highly%20classified%2C%20taking%20place%20at%20Area%2051%20in%20Nevada%20and%20hidden%20away%20from%20Soviet%20spy%20satellites.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EArea%2051%20workers%20were%20provided%20with%20rosters%20of%20Soviet%20satellites%2C%20detailing%20when%20certain%20ones%20would%20fly%20over%20the%20Nevada%20test%20site%20so%20they%20could%20conceal%20the%20prototypes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt%20was%20like%20a%20bus%20schedule%2C%20and%20it%20even%20told%20us%20whether%20it%20was%20an%20infrared%20satellite%20or%20what%20type%20it%20was%2C%26quot%3B%20TD%20Barnes%2C%20a%20former%20hypersonic%20flight%20specialist%20at%20Area%2051%2C%20told%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Faffiliate.insider.com%3Fh%3D4fade989e0e45b34450ac96fa11977a59dcfa97f1a6a65e85116599479c60885%26postID%3D65987221a62cdd3ed8f5807b%26postSlug%3Dhistory-of-a-12-spy-plane-2024-1%26site%3Dbi%26u%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.nationalgeographic.com%252Fscience%252Farticle%252F110520-area-51-secret-hid-craft-base-declassified-a-12-plane%5C%22%20data-autoaffiliated%3D%5C%22true%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ENational%20Geographic%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%202011.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20OXCART%20prototypes%20were%20tested%20outside%20atop%20tall%20poles%20to%20test%20their%20detection%20on%20radars%2C%20forcing%20workers%20to%20hide%20them%20in%20%26quot%3Bhoot%20and%20scoot%26quot%3B%20sheds%20when%20spy%20satellites%20were%20coming%20over%20the%20horizon.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BTo%20start%20working%20on%20the%20aircraft%20and%20then%20have%20to%20run%20it%20back%20into%20the%20hangar%20and%20then%20pull%20it%20out%20and%20then%20put%20it%20in%20and%20then%20pull%20it%20out%20%E2%80%94%20it%20gets%20to%20be%20quite%20a%20hassle%2C%26quot%3B%20Jim%20Freedman%2C%20a%20former%20Area%2051%20procurement%20manager%2C%20said%20in%20the%202011%20National%20Geographic%20Channel%20documentary%2C%20Area%2051%20Declassified.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20addition%20to%20the%20sheds%2C%20workers%20also%20crafted%20decoy%20prototypes%20out%20of%20cardboard%20and%20other%20materials%20to%20cast%20shadows%20and%20deceive%20the%20satellites.%20They%20also%20ran%20heaters%20to%20act%20as%20fake%20engines%20to%20make%20it%20appear%20as%20though%20planes%20had%20just%20landed.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAt%20least%20one%20of%20the%20A-12's%20numerous%20test%20flights%20didn't%20go%20according%20to%20plan%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fcia-area-51-spy-plane-national-geographic-a-12--2011-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecrashing%20in%20the%20desert%20outside%20Area%2051%3C%2Fa%3E.%20The%20US%20government%20was%20quick%20to%20cover%20up%20the%20incident%2C%20but%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Faffiliate.insider.com%3Fh%3D1dd376ab49874d0def2737ea7a2f63e678c8821f383270ff4703fe07be840e7d%26postID%3D65987221a62cdd3ed8f5807b%26postSlug%3Dhistory-of-a-12-spy-plane-2024-1%26site%3Dbi%26u%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.nationalgeographic.com%252Fhistory%252Farticle%252F110520-spy-plane-area-51-cover-up-crash-cia-conspiracy%5C%22%20data-autoaffiliated%3D%5C%22true%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edeclassified%20imagery%3C%2Fa%3E%20showed%20the%20scattered%20remnants%20of%20the%20plane%20and%20crews%20cleaning%20up%20the%20debris.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EPilot%20requirements%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%22356%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22An%20outside%20view%20of%20the%20A-12's%20cockpit.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659bb2706979d73718212695%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22237%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EAn%20outside%20view%20of%20the%20A-12's%20cockpit.%3Cp%3ECIA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThough%20the%20A-12%20touted%20impressive%20design%20features%2C%20it%20didn't%20have%20much%20legroom.%20Pilots%20had%20to%20be%20less%20than%20six%20feet%20tall%20and%20under%20175%20pounds%20just%20to%20fit%20into%20the%20single-seat%20cockpit.%20A%20typical%20flight%20would%20only%20have%20one%20crew%20member%20aboard.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPilots%20themselves%20also%20faced%20a%20strict%20set%20of%20criteria%20to%20fly%20the%20A-12.%20Candidates%20must%20have%20at%20least%202%2C000%20total%20flight%20hours%20%E2%80%94%20half%20of%20which%20should%20be%20in%20the%20latest%20high-performance%20fighter%20jets.%20They%20were%20also%20required%20to%20be%20married%2C%20emotionally%20stable%2C%20and%20between%2025%20and%2040%20years%20old.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOnly%2016%20candidates%20met%20the%20qualifications%20and%20went%20through%20an%20extensive%20security%20and%20medical%20review%2C%20narrowing%20the%20pool%20to%20five%20people.%20A%20second%20review%20process%20yielded%20six%20more.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EA-12%20pilots'%20protective%20thermal%20pressure%20suit%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221600%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20protective%20pressure%20suit%20worn%20by%20A-12%20pilots.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659bb3901c5c7b8c9a0eb146%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221280%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EA%20protective%20pressure%20suit%20worn%20by%20A-12%20pilots.%3Cp%3ECIA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EBecause%20of%20the%20plane's%20supersonic%20speeds%2C%20the%20skin%20of%20the%20plane%20could%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cia.gov%2Fstatic%2Fb45f5f8f5e4937963d9e9931313d84a4%2FArchangel-CIAs-Supersonic-A-12-Reconnaissance-Aircraft.pdf%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eheat%20up%20to%20600%20degrees%20Fahrenheit%20and%201%2C000%20degrees%20near%20the%20engine%3C%2Fa%3E.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cia.gov%2Flegacy%2Fmuseum%2Fartifact%2Fa-12-full-pressure-suit%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EPilots%20had%20to%20wear%20suits%3C%2Fa%3E%20outfitted%20with%20thermal%20insulation%2C%20pressure%20control%2C%20cooling%2C%20and%20a%20life%20support%20system%20to%20protect%20them%20from%20fluctuating%20extreme%20temperatures%20and%20pressure%20changes%20in%20the%20event%20of%20a%20high-altitude%20bailout.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20cockpit%20also%20had%20an%20air%20conditioning%20system%20to%20keep%20pilots%20cool%20during%20flight.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EEjection%20instructions%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%22236%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Emergency%20ejection%20instructions%20for%20pilots%20on%20their%20A-12%20suits'%20sleeves%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659bb6076979d737182126be%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22315%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20A-12%20suit%20sleeves%20had%20emergency%20instructions%20for%20pilots%20to%20refer%20to%20upon%20ejection.%3Cp%3ECIA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3ETheir%20suits%20also%20featured%20emergency%20instructions%20to%20refer%20to%20in%20case%20they%20need%20to%20eject%20themselves%20from%20the%20plane.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EReplaced%20by%20spy%20satellites%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%224368%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20Lockheed%20A-12%20in%20front%20of%20Manhattan's%20skyline%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659baf7e6979d73718212677%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%222912%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20Lockheed%20A-12%20looks%20over%20sits%20in%20front%20of%20Manhattan's%20skyline%20at%20the%20Intrepid%20Sea-Air-Space%20Museum.%3Cp%3EMichael%20Nagle%2FGetty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20its%20first%20flight%20in%20October%201963%2C%20the%20A-12%20was%20deemed%20fully%20operational%20in%201965%2C%20achieving%20record-breaking%20speeds%20of%20up%20to%202%2C200%20mph%20(Mach%203)%20%E2%80%94%20three%20times%20the%20speed%20of%20sound%20%E2%80%94%20and%20altitudes%20up%20to%2090%2C000%20feet.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEven%20today%2C%20the%20A-12%20maintains%20records%20for%20the%20highest%20speed%20and%20altitude%20achieved%20by%20piloted%20jet%20with%20air-breathing%20engines.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EDespite%20its%20record-breaking%20innovations%2C%20the%20A-12%20only%20flew%20in%20one%20reconnaissance%20operation%2C%20codenamed%20Black%20Shield%2C%20from%20May%201967%20to%20May%201968.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20A-12%20captured%20high-quality%20imagery%20that%20could%20be%20processed%20and%20interpreted%20within%20hours%20of%20landing.%20Three%20A-12s%20flew%2029%20missions%20over%20East%20Asia%2C%20extracting%20intelligence%20for%20US%20forces%20during%20the%20Vietnam%20War.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAround%20the%20same%20time%2C%20the%20US%20began%20to%20deploy%20Corona%20photo%20reconnaissance%20satellites%20to%20gather%20intelligence%20about%20the%20Soviet%20Union.%20The%20satellites%20produced%20lower-quality%20imagery%20than%20the%20A-12%20and%20were%20slower%20in%20getting%20imagery%20to%20photo-interpreters%2C%20but%20they%20were%20impervious%20to%20anti-aircraft%20missiles%20and%20less%20likely%20to%20provoke%20foreign%20nations%20than%20surveillance%20overflights.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20after%20a%20U-2%20plane%20was%20shot%20down%20over%20the%20Soviet%20Union%20and%20its%20pilot%2C%20Francis%20Gary%20Powers%2C%20was%20captured%20in%20May%201960%2C%20most%20spy%20planes%20shifted%20to%20missions%20near%20their%20borders%20while%20still%20in%20international%20airspace.%20The%20U-2%20and%20RC-135%20Rivet%20Joint%20are%20still%20flown%20on%20reconnaissance%20missions%20by%20the%20US%20Air%20Force.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAmid%20concerns%20that%20Soviet%20radars%20could%20soon%20catch%20up%20with%20the%20A-12's%20innovation%2C%20President%20Lyndon%20B.%20Johnson%20ordered%20the%20retirement%20of%20the%20A-12%20in%201968.%20The%20US%20then%20proceeded%20with%20its%20successor%2C%20the%20SR-71%2C%20famed%20for%20its%20reconnaissance%20missions%20during%20the%20Cold%20War.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EThe%20SR-71%20Blackbird%2C%20the%20A-12's%20successor%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%223000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Lockheed%20SR%2071%20Blackbird%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F54885d08eab8ea5b248b456c%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%222350%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20SR-71%20Blackbird.%3Cp%3EJudson%20Brohmer%2FUSAF%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20SR-71%20Blackbird%20was%20less%20likely%20to%20be%20detected%20on%20enemy%20radar%20than%20the%20A-12%2C%20carrying%20additional%20optical%20and%20radar%20imagery%20systems.%20The%20two-seater%20Blackbird%20was%20much%20larger%20than%20the%20A-12%2C%20measuring%20about%20six%20feet%20longer%20than%20the%20A-12%20and%20weighing%2015%2C000%20pounds%20more.%20It%20was%20slower%2C%20but%20it%20had%20a%20longer%20range%20in%20between%20refueling.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAs%20spy%20satellite%20programs%20gained%20more%20traction%20in%20foreign%20reconnaissance%2C%20the%20SR-71%20suffered%20the%20same%20fate%20as%20its%20predecessor%2C%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cia.gov%2Fstories%2Fstory%2Foxcart-vs-blackbird-do-you-know-the-difference%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ethe%20last%20Blackbird%20was%20decommissioned%20on%20January%2026%2C%201990%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EThe%20YF-12%2C%20an%20armed%20A-12%20variant%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20YF-12A%20at%20the%20NASA%20Flight%20Research%20Center.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659bb8571c5c7b8c9a0eb184%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22860%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20YF-12A%20at%20the%20NASA%20Flight%20Research%20Center.%3Cp%3ENASA%2FDVIDS%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EDeveloped%20in%20the%201960s%20under%20Project%20Kedlock%2C%20an%20extension%20of%20Project%20Oxcart%2C%20the%20YF-12%20came%20just%20before%20the%20SR-71.%20It%20could%20travel%20at%20Mach%203%20speeds%20and%20fly%20at%20altitudes%20up%20to%2080%2C000%20feet.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20YF-12%20was%20designed%20to%20intercept%20Soviet%20bombers%20at%20long%20range%20and%20high-speed%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Eand%20was%20armed%20with%20three%20air-to-air%20missiles.%20But%20due%20to%20cost-cutting%20measures%20amid%20the%20war%20in%20Southeast%20Asia%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nationalmuseum.af.mil%2FVisit%2FMuseum-Exhibits%2FFact-Sheets%2FDisplay%2FArticle%2F195777%2Flockheed-yf-12a%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ESecretary%20of%20Defense%20Robert%20McNamara%20cancelled%20the%20Kedlock%20Project%20in%201968%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20and%20the%20YF-12%20was%20never%20deployed.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EThe%20M-21%2C%20a%20drone-carrying%20A-12%20variant%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%223122%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20Lockheed%20M-21%20stealth%20reconnaissance%20plane%20in%20flight%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F659bb91c1c5c7b8c9a0eb195%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%222456%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EA%20Lockheed%20M-21%20stealth%20reconnaissance%20plane%20in%20flight%20over%20the%20Mojave%20Desert.%3Cp%3EMuseum%20of%20Flight%20Foundation%2FCORBIS%2FCorbis%20via%20Getty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EBuilt%20for%20the%20CIA%20under%20Project%20Tagboard%2C%20the%20M-21%20was%20a%20modified%20A-12%20designed%20to%20carry%20an%20unmanned%20drone%20for%20gathering%20intelligence%20over%20hostile%20territories.%20To%20prevent%20confusion%2C%20the%20modified%20A-12%20was%20named%20the%20M-21%20%E2%80%94%20standing%20for%20mother%20%E2%80%94%20while%20the%20drone%20it%20carried%20was%20called%20the%20D-21%20%E2%80%94%20standing%20for%20daughter.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOnly%20two%20M-21%20airframes%20were%20manufactured%2C%20one%20of%20which%20was%20destroyed%20in%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.museumofflight.org%2Fexhibits-and-events%2Faircraft%2Flockheed-m-21-blackbird%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edrone%20launching%20incident%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%201966.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EElon%20Musk's%20son%2C%20X%20%C3%86%20A-12%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%223279%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Elon%20Musk%20holds%20a%20microphone%20while%20looking%20at%20his%20son%2C%20X